In the following weeks, Ping would activate the Airloom and suddenly
find herself transported to familiar aisles, surrounded by fluorescent
lights and refrigeration units. Other times, there was only Ama's voice,
disembodied but clear, offering unsolicited advice on electrolyte brick
flavors or explaining how to reheat leftover dumplings.

Simultaneously, Ping began to hear reports of unexplainable events
across the province's snack kiosks and convenience stores. Grandparents
purchasing heatwraps were thanked by name. Children buying spicy mango
jerky were auto-credited with coupons for free second bags, each one
reading, "just this once!" Across the tangled mesh of KnotLine protocols
and deprecated Lucky Star store codebase residuals, Ama's consciousness
had scattered like light through a prism.

And sometimes, late at night, as rain pelted the windows, Ping would sit
with her daughter and whisper stories about a stubborn old woman who ran
a magical store that always looked out for you.
